@node intro "Introduction"

@{b}Introduction@{ub}

  WBBump is a "tool" to make your Workbench a bit nicer to look at.

  A bumpmapped logo is put on your Workbench(tm) screen or any other
  public screen of your wish. The lightsource of the bumpmapping is
  your mouse pointer!

  THIS IS NOT A HACK - This program should be system friendly.
  If it dosn't work on your system, please send a @{"bug report" LINK author}.
@endnode



@node features "Features"

@{b}Features@{ub}

Main features of WBBump 2.0 Beta2 include:

  * Looks nice :)

  * System friendly

  * It's a Commodity

  * @{"Plugin support" LINK plugins}

  * Uses datatypes for bumpmap loading

  * Bumpmapping rutine is written in assembler

  * Multithreaded drawing

  * Dosn't slow down other programs (low task priority)

  * Seperate code for 8bit / truecolor graphics

  * Doesn't update display if mouse isn't moved
    or screen isn't frontmost

  * Source code available

  * Completely free
@endnode



@node req "Requirements"

@{b}Requirements@{ub}

WBBump currently requires:

  * Kickstart/Workbench 3.0

  * An 68020 cpu

  * Cybergraphics V39+ OR Picasso96 V??
    Experimental AGA/ECS/OCS support is included in this release

  * Workbench running in backdrop mode

  * a PNG datatype will be handy for some of the examples...
    Get one at http://www.aminet.net/aminetbin/find?png+datatype

@endnode



@node inst "Installation"

@{b}Installation@{ub}

I have not written an install script because WBBump is very easy
to install.

  * First of all, make sure that your Workbench runs in Backdrop mode.

  * Copy the WBBump drawer to a place on your harddisk of
    your choice.

  * Add this line to your S:user-startup:
    Assign WBBump: {directory where WBBump was copied}

  * Copy one of the sample projects to  your WBStartup drawer.

  * @{"Configure" LINK conf} the tooltypes of WBBump

  * Reboot

@endnode


@node conf "Configuration"

@{b}Configuration@{ub}

  WBBump is configured with the tooltypes.
  To configure select the WBBump icon, or the project icon
  that starts it, and select @{i}Information@{ui} from the @{i}Icon@{ui} menu.

  () around a tooltype means that it is disabled.

  If you're not quite sure what @{i}Tool Types@{ui} or the @{i}WBStartup drawer@{ui} is, please
  consult your Workbench manual.

  The following tooltypes are available:

  @{b}SCREENNAME@{ub}={name}

    name is the name of a public screen to open WBBump on.
    If this tooltype is not present, the default public screen is used.
    If name is @{i}Workbench@{ui} WBBump will open on the Workbench screen.


  @{b}BUMPMAP@{ub}={filename}

    Specifies which file to use as a bumpmap.
    Defaults to "WBBump:Bumpmaps/Amiga.ilbm".

    You can use any type of picture that you have a datatype for, ie
    pictures that you can view with the Multiview utility.

    Color 0 of the picture will be the lowest part of the bumpmap, and
    Color 255 will be the highest.

    The image must currently have excactly 256 colors.

    changes for version 2.0+

      BUMPMAP is now an external plugin.
      (Plugins/image.wbbplugin).

      Filenames with spaces in them must now be enclosed in double quotes.
      ie. @{b}BUMPMAP=WBBump:Bumpmaps/Intel Outside.png@{ub} becomes
      @{b}BUMPMAP="WBBump:Bumpmaps/Intel Outside.png"@{ub}


  @{b}DEPTH@{ub}={number: [1;8]}

    Sets the number of brightness levels to use for the bumpmapping.
    A DEPTH of 4 means 2^4 levels = 16 levels, which is the default.
    The higher the depth, the longer time it takes to start WBBump on
    screens with <= 256 colors.
    This tooltype is ignored for 15/16/24 bit screens.


  @{b}TASKPRI@{ub}={number: [-128;127]}

    Sets the task priority of the WBBump task.
    If you don't know what this means the default of -100 should be fine.
    TASKPRI should NOT be set above -1 if you don't know what you're doing!


  @{b}POSITIONX@{ub}={number: [0;]}

    Vertical position of bumpmap on the screen, measured in pixels.
    If this tooltype is absent, the image will be vertically centered.
    Please don't set this value higher than {screen width} - {bumpmap width}
    or strange things might happen. Checks for this will be added in the
    future.


  @{b}POSITIONY@{ub}={number: [0;]}

    Horisentical position of bumpmap on the screen, measured in pixels.
    If this tooltype is absent, the image will be horisentically centered.
    Please don't set this value higher than {screen height} - {bumpmap height}
    or strange things might happen. Checks for this will be added in the
    future.


  @{b}LIGHTCOLOR@{ub}={red: [0;256]} {blue: [0;256]} {green: [0;256]}
    Specifies the color of the light.
    Default is LIGHTCOLOR=256 256 256
    The lightcolor can currently only be set for 8 bit screens.


  @{b}STARTDELAY@{ub}={seconds: [0;100]}

    Sets a number of seconds that WBBump should wait before starting.
    This is useful if you start WBBump from the WBStartup drawer, because
    if it starts before your background picture (if any) is loaded, you
    will not have the desired effect. If you have problems making it look
    right, try setting this tooltype to a value higher than 0.


  @{b}DONOTWAIT@{ub}

    This tooltype should allways be present.
    If not, WBBump can not be started from WBStartup.


  @{b}STARTPRI@{ub}={number: [-128;127]}

    Sets WBBumps start priority with which Workbench starts this program
    when started from WBStartup. Unlike with STARTPRI, priority here means
    the order in which the WBStartup programs are started. A program with
    STARTPRI=10 is started earlier than a program with STARTPRI=0.
    Normally STARTPRI=-128 is the best choice for WBBump.

@endnode




@node control "Controling WBBump"

@{b}Controling WBBump@{ub}

  WBBump is a Commodity and can be controlled by the Exhange program present
  on your Workbench disk.
  Please consult your Workbench manual on how to use this program.

  The following commodity commands are supported:

  * Show interface - Pops up the Workbench info requester for the icon
                     you started wbbump from.
                     If your filesystem supports notification, WBBump will
                     restart with the new settings when you save the icon.

  * Disable        - Freezes WBBump

  * Enable         - Starts it again

  * Remove         - Make WBBump quit

@endnode



@node plugins "Plugin support"

@{b}Plugin support@{ub}

  From version 2.0 WBBump supports external plugins.

  Plugins are external libraries that are used to generate bumpmaps runtime.

  Currently plugins must be located in WBBump:Plugins/


@{b}How to use plugins@{ub}

  Plugins are activated with tooltypes.
  Each plugin has it's own tooltype that activates and controls the plugin.

  The following plugins are in the main archive:

  @{b}image.wbbplugin@{ub}

    Tooltype: BUMPMAP=FILENAME/A

    Example:  BUMPMAP=WBBump:Bumpmaps/Amiga.ilbm

    Loads an image with datatypes and uses it as a bumpmap

    You can use any type of picture that you have a datatype for, ie
    pictures that you can view with the Multiview utility.

    Color 0 of the picture will be the lowest part of the bumpmap, and
    Color 255 will be the highest.

    The image must currently have excactly 256 colors.


  @{b}blur.wbbplugin@{ub}

    Tooltype: PLUGIN_BLUR=PASSES/N

    Examples: PLUGIN_BLUR
              PLUGIN_BLUR=PASSES 2

    Blurs the output of the previous plugin PASSES number of times.

    The more passes, the more blurred the bumpmap will be.


  @{b}clock.wbbplugin@{ub}

    Tooltype: PLUGIN_CLOCK=SIT/S,CET_OFFSET/N,SUMMERTIME/S

    Examples: PLUGIN_CLOCK
              PLUGIN_CLOCK=SIT CET_OFFSET -2 SUMMERTIME

    SIT         : Display time in Swatch BEATS (Internet time)
    CET_OFFSET  : Offset in hours from CET (Central European Time)
                : (Only needed for SIT)
    SUMMERTIME  : Specify that time should be ajusted with -1h because
                  of "Daylight Saving" period

    Please note, that this plugin requires a PNG datatype installed.


  @{b}null.wbbplugin@{ub}
  @{b}invert.wbbplugin@{ub}

    These plugins aren't really useful for anything other than testing,
    I guess you shouldn't use them.


  @{b}Order is important!@{ub}

    Please note that the plugins are executed in the order that they are
    specified in the tooltypes.


  @{b}Developing plugins@{ub}

    Please refer to @{"Developper information" LINK dev} if you wish to make your own plugins.

@endnode




@node dev "Developper information"

@{b}Developper information@{ub}

  The complete sourcecode is a seperate archive called
  WBBump{version}_src.(lha|lzx)

  You need EC (E compiler) V3.3 or compatible, PhxAss and GNU make to
  compile the sources.
  Maybe other versions of EC will work, I haven't tried.
  I honestly don't know which versions of make will work, mine is
  @{i}GNU Make version 3.75, by Richard Stallman and Roland McGrath.@{ui}
  (non ixemul version)
  Please note that ixemul versions of make might complain when building
  the plugins.

  Remember that you MUST obey the terms in the @{"GNU GENERAL PUBLIC LICENSE" LINK "COPYING/main"}
  if you decide to compile your own version.


@{b}About plugins@{ub}

  Please contact me if you want to make your own plugins, as the plugin-
  interface is still subject to change.

@endnode


@node history "History"

@{b}History@{ub}


@{b}2.0 final (build 634) -  1999/6/29@{ub}

  * Fixed bug with AGA (bumpmap was always on grey background)
    Now it should be applied on the existing background as the CGX version
    (Thanks for the help @{"Daniel" LINK thanks})

  * Removed annoying requester when not started from a project


@{b}2.0b2 (build 614) -  1999/5/16@{ub}

  * Added AGA/ECS/OCS support (experimental).

  * Fixed blur plugin (It didn't work at all...)

  * Added Clock plugin (digital and internet time)

  * Bugfixes: chrashes with two instances (when closing)

  * Disabled multithreading - it caused some strange chrashes

  * Fixed examples

  * WBBump no longer needs the WBBump: assign
    (But the examples still do)


@{b}2.0b1 (build 569) -  1999/5/8@{ub}

  * Fixed bug that would cause WBBump to reload instead of quit, when
    task was sent a break signal

  * Converted big examples to PNG

  * Changed some ReadPixel()'s to ReadPixelLine8(), thanks to
    @{"Gunther Nikl" LINK thanks} for noticing.
    Result is a general speedup in the startup phase.

  * (hopefully) removed CyberGuard hit (read from adr $20).
    I still can't figure out why MuForce didn't get it?
    Thanks to @{"Duncan Gibb" LINK thanks} for reporting.

  * WBBump now only renders if the screen it's on is the frontmost one.
    before it would check for the active screen rather than the frontmost one.
    Thanks to @{"Michal Bartczak" LINK thanks} for noticing.

  * Plugin support, see @{"Plugins" LINK plugins}

  * New tooltypes POSITIONX, POSITIONY and LIGHTCOLOR


@{b}1.3  (build 286) -  1999/04/29@{ub}

  * Aminet release

  * Added notification on icon which started WBBump

  * Added @{"Show interface" LINK control} Commodities command

  * Taskname is now a bit more informative (for those that care :)


@{b}1.2  (build 270) -  1999/04/28@{ub}

  * Big speedup in 8bit code (2 pass E/asm -> 1 pass asm)

  * Converted some examples to GIF for smaller archive

  * Bugfixes in thread code

  * Added "Intel Outside" example project


@{b}1.1  (build 244) -  1999/04/27@{ub}

  * Complete rework of bitmap handling

  * Added datatypes support

  * Added seperate thread for drawing


@{b}1.0  (build 142) -  1999/04/18@{ub}
  Initial version


@endnode



@node future "Future"

@{b}Future@{ub}

This is improvements that I would like to add to WBBump
(no particular order)

  * Perhaps make an install-script if it's requested

  * More assembler optimizations

  * PPC support

  * More plugins: waves, waterdrop, etc.

  * Prefs editor

  * The errormessages are probably not very informative.
    Please contact @{"me" LINK author} if you get a strange errormessage!

  * "Distance sensitivity" option

  * Support notifyintuition.library or screennotify.libray such that
    screenmode can be changed without having to close WBBump.

If there's something you miss, please mail @{"me" LINK author}
Also the more requests I get for a certain feature, the more likely
it is to be implemented.

@endnode



